! Examples

!! Example: dropping a Thunderbird `.eml`

Thunderbird's drag-and-drop puts the original RFC 5322 source on the clipboard as an `.eml` File with `type=""` (Chrome strips the MIME — see `tw-outlook-drag-empty-mime` memory). file-upload's dropzone falls back to the file's extension and maps `.eml` → `message/rfc822`; that MIME is allow-listed from file-upload ≥ 0.1.24. The msg-import pipeline matches both `application/vnd.ms-outlook` and `message/rfc822`, so the same three-tiddler output tree appears:

```
team-update.eml                                      ← parent (type: message/rfc822)
team-update.eml.email                                ← markdown + frontmatter
team-update.eml.attachments/att_report.pdf           ← typed application/pdf, gets its own thumbnail
```

The `.eml` path uses Python's stdlib `email` module — no extra pip install needed. Inline images embedded as `multipart/related` are surfaced with their `Content-ID` intact so the existing `cid:` rewriting in the markdown body still works.

!! Example: drop a meeting invite

After dropping `kickoff.msg` into a `<$file-dropzone>`, the resulting `kickoff.msg.email` tiddler looks roughly like:

```
---
type: text/x-frontmattered-markdown
msg-subject: "Project Apollo kickoff"
msg-from: "Alice Smith <alice@example.com>"
msg-to:
  - bob@example.com
  - carol@example.com
msg-cc: []
msg-bcc: []
msg-date: 2026-05-13T08:42:00+00:00
msg-message-id: <CAJq8...@mail.example.com>
msg-in-reply-to: ""
msg-has-attachments: yes
tags: email
---

# Project Apollo kickoff

Hi all,

Let's get the kickoff scheduled for next Tuesday. See the attached agenda...

![](/files/email/_derived/kickoff.msg/cid_logo123.png)
```

The agenda PDF lives at `kickoff.msg.attachments/att_agenda.pdf` with `_artifact_source = kickoff.msg` and `type: application/pdf` (file-pipeline ≥ 0.1.10 infers the MIME from the filename; older versions defaulted every output to `image/png`). Because the inferred MIME matches the PDF pipeline, file-pipeline's nested-trigger fires automatically and produces:

```
kickoff.msg                                          ← parent .msg
kickoff.msg.email                                    ← markdown + frontmatter (from msg pipeline)
kickoff.msg.attachments/att_agenda.pdf               ← the PDF attachment (typed application/pdf)
kickoff.msg.attachments/att_agenda.pdf._thumbnail    ← thumbnail (from pdf pipeline)
kickoff.msg.attachments/att_agenda.pdf.extracted     ← text extraction (from pdf pipeline, if enabled)
```

Each layer carries an `_artifact_source` field pointing one level up; file-upload's cascade walks the chain transitively so a single delete on `kickoff.msg` clears every layer + the entire `_derived/kickoff.msg/` directory tree.

!! Example: an email with a forwarded .msg attached

A `digest.msg` that contains a forwarded `original.msg` as a non-inline attachment produces:

```
digest.msg
digest.msg.email
digest.msg.attachments/att_original.msg           ← typed application/vnd.ms-outlook
digest.msg.attachments/att_original.msg.email     ← from recursive msg pipeline
digest.msg.attachments/att_original.msg.attachments/*   ← grandchildren if any
```

Each recursion adds the parent's URI to a `seen` map. If `original.msg` happens to be byte-identical to `digest.msg` (e.g. self-referential payload), the nested pipeline skips it instead of looping forever.

!! Example: enable the LLM summary step

```
<$action-setfield $tiddler="$:/config/rimir/msg-import/llm-summary" text="yes"/>
```

Re-drop a message. A new `kickoff.msg.summary` tiddler appears with the LLM-produced digest (TL;DR + decisions + action items + open questions, per `prompts/email-summary.tid`).

!! Example: override the LLM provider per dropzone

```
<$file-dropzone pipeline="auto"
  prop-system-prompt="$:/my/custom-system-prompt"
  prop-provider="anthropic"
  prop-model="claude-opus-4-7"/>
```

The three `prop-*` attributes are passed through file-pipeline's client to the LLM step. They take precedence over llm-connect's global defaults but lose to step-level fields set in the pipeline tiddler.
